      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis QoI validation — RH index prediction",
      "description": "The CFD model was exercised across all five CPB flow-speed operating points (2 L/min @ 2500 RPM through 6 L/min @ 4500 RPM). Predicted normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) values were post-processed using the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage accumulation model. The validation exercise drew on the Morrison et al. (2019) experimental dataset, which characterises RBC lysis rates in a centrifugal blood pump platform under continuous-flow ventricular assist device conditions. Agreement between predicted and measured NIH was reported as within ±18% across all operating points, which the assessment team characterised as satisfactory given the MRL 2 requirement. The dataset is well-characterised, peer-reviewed, and widely cited in the rotary blood pump literature. No systematic bias in over- or under-prediction was identified across the operating envelope tested. The assessment team concluded that the validation evidence supports confidence in the model's ability to rank hemolysis severity across the five CPB operating points.",
      "metric": "Normalised Index of Hemolysis (NIH)",
      "agreementTolerance": "±18%",
      "assessmentOutcome": "Satisfactory",
      "note": "comparedAgainst link intentionally absent — W-AR-05 trigger surface. The Morrison 2019 dataset originates from a VAD operating regime (continuous low-flow, high-pressure-head, long shear-exposure residence times) that differs from the short-duration, higher-flow CPB regime in the declared COU. The narrative does not examine this applicability gap."
    },
